comment: GIANT CAVEAT -- Gold has intrinsic value because it can be used in manufacturing of goods.  As gold's market value skyrockets, though, the cost of using it for electronics, false teeth or jewelry skyrockets accordingly.  Since electronic items are bought by many non-gold owners, they won't be able to afford the products.  Cost shall force gold's replacement by substitute materials.  Gold shall suffer de facto LOSS of its intrinsic value, becoming a speculative asset.

author: @ramkumarrealm
comment:
Gold price surge: Gold‚Äôs price shot past $4,000 per ounce in October 2025, driven by eroding confidence in the US dollar, increased geopolitical tensions, and economic uncertainty, including the impact of Trump's trade war and doubts about the Federal Reserve‚Äôs independence.

Flight to gold: Traditionally, crises led investors to buy US dollars and treasuries, but now gold has become the preferred safe-haven asset. Central banks and investors are rapidly buying gold.

Debasement trade: The sharp rise in gold, parallel to the US dollar‚Äôs decline, reflects a loss of faith in government-backed bonds and currencies. Gold‚Äôs independence from government influence and its lack of counterparty risk makes it especially appealing in uncertain times.

Federal Reserve and inflation: Pressure from the White House on the Fed, lower interest rates, and inflation further increase gold‚Äôs appeal compared to cash and bonds.

Geopolitical context: After Russia‚Äôs 2022 invasion of Ukraine and subsequent Western asset freezes, countries started diversifying away from the dollar to protect against future US sanctions‚Äîleading central banks to heavily increase gold reserves. China has emerged as the biggest gold consumer and buyer, aiming to reduce reliance on the dollar.

Declining dollar dominance: The dollar‚Äôs share of global reserves has slipped since 2000. Trade conflicts, sanctions, and inflation have prompted trading partners to reconsider dollar-based trade.

ETF demand and alternatives: Gold-backed ETFs provide easy access for investors. September 2025 saw huge ETF inflows, and silver and platinum prices have also rallied. Cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are viewed as alternative haven assets by some.

Future outlook and volatility: Gold‚Äôs rally reflects the fragile geopolitical climate, weakening old alliances and forming new ones. While some worry about a bubble, banking analysts expect gains to continue as long as global tensions persist.

Flight to gold: Traditionally, crises led investors to buy US dollars and treasuries, but now gold has become the preferred safe-haven asset. Central banks and investors are rapidly buying gold. Debasement trade: The sharp rise in gold, parallel to the US dollar‚Äôs decline, reflects a loss of faith in government-backed bonds and currencies. Gold‚Äôs independence from government influence and its lack of counterparty risk makes it especially appealing in uncertain times. Federal Reserve and inflation: Pressure from the White House on the Fed, lower interest rates, and inflation further increase gold‚Äôs appeal compared to cash and bonds. Geopolitical context: After Russia‚Äôs 2022 invasion of Ukraine and subsequent Western asset freezes, countries started diversifying away from the dollar to protect against future US sanctions‚Äîleading central banks to heavily increase gold reserves. China has emerged as the biggest gold consumer and buyer, aiming to reduce reliance on the dollar. Declining dollar dominance: The dollar‚Äôs share of global reserves has slipped since 2000. Trade conflicts, sanctions, and inflation have prompted trading partners to reconsider dollar-based trade. ETF demand and alternatives: Gold-backed ETFs provide easy access for investors. September 2025 saw huge ETF inflows, and silver and platinum prices have also rallied. Cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are viewed as alternative haven assets by some. Future outlook and volatility: Gold‚Äôs rally reflects the fragile geopolitical climate, weakening old alliances and forming new ones. While some worry about a bubble, banking analysts expect gains to continue as long as global tensions persist.

comment: Basel 3 has classified allocated physical gold (not ‚Äúpaper‚Äù gold) as a Tier 1 asset, meaning it‚Äôs as strong and liquid as cash. That means banks can store gold in their reserve with the same confidence as cash. If you are a country, like China, which wants to hedge and be independent from the U.S. dollar, your central bank could now hoard physical gold, which is exactly what‚Äôs happening.   The demand for gold will go down once sovereign central banks say they have ‚Äúenough‚Äù gold.

comment: It‚Äôs always advisable to invest judiciously, keep a stop loss figure. Shuffle between debt and equity wherever the ratio goes too off your target. As for the target, I recommend a Ratio like this Debt % should be equal to your age in years. If you are 20, debt is 20%, reset in equity. If the market falls or rises drastically, your debt % will change, which you should rebalance to 20% and bring back equity to 80%. Thus you would have bought low or booked profit depending on if it was a crash or a bull run, you still have the chance to improve you financial level by following Mills Wiesener‚Äôs program.

author: @happycakes1946
comment:
Value does not come from work... Work can add value, but people don't farm because they want to work.. Value is highly subjective, for example a glass of water has little value to you right now probably, but imagine being stranded in the desert with no water for days. You'd pay anything. 

The currency is the most traded commodity, for it to be stable it's best if it's something that everyone wants, but is hard to acquire (takes hard work). This way, the growth of the economy is tied to real assets and regular people's savings will earn a real interest rate. The problem is paper allows margin which amplifies speculation - the banks lend claims on nothing - creating them costs them very little,  the people effectively become debt slaves to the banks. Instead of earning interest, their savings are debased through excessive lending.

author: @pringleeatingdingodile
comment:
Your comment may seem like a dumb comment to some, but it's probably the smartest comment here.

I guess we trade hard, rare, bearer assets for imaginary paper assets, in order to more easily spend them -- fiat currency (currently) is more liquid, divisible, and fungible.

For the world to finally correct itself, heal itself, and move backwards towards a more fair society, we ideally need to go back to a currency pegged by a hard, rare, bearer asset that can be held in custody by nation states and corporations as a means of final settlement -- be it gold, bitcoin, or a weighted blend of both. Moving away from the gold standard, towards fiat currency is the worst thing that ever happened. It has lead to the enshittification of everything, shrinkflation, skimpflation, decades of theft of the working class' productivity, and increased inequality. It only really benefit those closest to the banks that do the printing, as they are first in line to swap their made up money for hard assets like gold, wine, real estate, stocks etc. etc.

Fiat currency is so evil, that even after my above rant, people still won't get it. It's so fcking evil.

author: @Siddharth-Singh-Fx
comment:
Over the next three quarters, close attention should be paid to the evolving macroeconomic backdrop as policy normalization, liquidity recalibration, and real yield trajectories begin to converge. This window will likely offer greater clarity on the medium-term equilibrium for gold, particularly as inflation expectations, central bank purchase programs, and geopolitical risk premia interplay with broader risk sentiment.

In the near term, bullion remains structurally supported, with positioning metrics and term-structure dislocations across the derivatives curve underscoring heightened speculative interest. Elevated cross-asset volatility and deteriorating equity risk-adjusted returns continue to reinforce the narrative of gold as both a convex hedge and a liquidity-proxy trade. The latest CFTC and ETF flow data further corroborate a pronounced rotation toward precious metals, reflecting a tactical preference for hard assets over duration- or beta-sensitive exposures.
